<a href="javascript:card_browser(72)">Goblin Runner</a>s x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(73)">Goblin Scavengers</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(86)">Moria Scout</a> x2<br>
Trolls Keyward x2<br>
Ulaire Enquea x1<br>
<br>
Possessions<br>
Cave Trolls Chain x1<br>
Cave Trolls Hammer x1<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(75)">Goblin Scimitar</a> x4<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Note: I&#39;m reposting Ghost with a few changes in the hopes of getting some more reviews this time. :) Thanks.<br>
<br>
Intro<br>
This is a Moria Choke Deck in the style of the infamous &#39;Don&#39;t Pee in The (Twilight) Pool&#39; by Alex Tennet. A nearly indestructible (and invisible) Aragorn leads Frodo on the path of least resistance, inhibiting the opponents card cycling, while Moria orcs rip his fellowship to shreds. Ghost uses a few tricks to slow the trickle of twilight to a veritable halt.<br>
<br>
Fellowship<br>
There are only two goals here: keep Frodo alive and kicking and prevent twilight. No Stranger, and Reluctant Adventurer are present and accounted for in most denial decks, but Gandalf&#39;s Wisdom is remarkably absent. Gandalf is a great guy and while we wouldn&#39;t want his clunky self cluttering our deck, his brilliance shines through with this card. All the athelas&#39;, the sword, shield, bow and armor are all free. That is potentially -7 twilight, identical to a first turn No Stranger. There are only 6 cards that cost twilight in the deck: 2 Bounders, Thrarin, Pippin, Saga of Elendil and Mithril-Coat. Each costs 1 except Pippin (1 for playing 1 for moving). You won&#39;t always want to play these cards because of this. Stealth does not add shadow except for a few events because<br>
You will of course MOVE ONLY ONCE A TURN. I can&#39;t stress this enough. One less move from you means one less discarded card from his/her achingly cluttered hand. The only case you might double move is if they are sitting on site eight, you can&#39;t kill them on site nine, and they have moved only once each turn so you are on site seven. Careful even then, as it may be suicidal: site eight will be 10 twilight, nine will be 9 and there is nothing you can do about it.<br>
So lets say on the first turn (bidding 2 to go second) you play a Wisdom and get out Thrarin - 4 pool. Second turn you get the Coat - 3 pool. Third turn you get a bounder and a No Stranger at council courtyard - 4 pool. Fifth turn - 7 pool. Sixth turn - 4 pool. Seventh - 7 pool. By now the game should be over and against anything but Moria you&#39;ll have fought maybe 3-4 minions, no more than 1 or 2 a turn. Frankly this deck does have some trouble with Moria, but you do have protection. 2 Paths, the mighty Ghost of Numenor himself -  Aragorn RotN, Bow, Stealth, Bounders, Thrarin and Pippin should help keep you alive at least long enough to kill them. Now on to the killing... ;)<br>
<br>
Shadow<br>
SMS Inc. Standard Moria Swarm it is and none the worse for it. Few other cultures are so intent on slaughtering the ring-bearer. Hefty Trolls and massive swarms aside, Moria is second to none at efficient twilight use and card cycling. The most obvious example would be using TaC to toss three duplicate possessions, pulling a scavenger his scimitar and an extra card at +1 twilight due to your 4 goblin armories (bwahaha). That is an extreme case, but even lesser versions are essential to this deck, both in keeping Frodo alive and for pulling off massive swarms. <br>
As for the few variations... The Goblin Domain is great because your opponent won&#39;t be drawing their companions as soon as they hoped to with the choke in place and this prevents a late game come back. The Flankers are simply my preference over Wallcrawlers. I find that 11Str -2 archery or protection from paths and direct archery for 5(or 2) is better than 6-8Str -1 archery for 2. Feel free to contradict.<br>
<br>
The Sites<br>
These are straightforward: Hobbiton Woods blocks the muchly hated weatherhills/weathertops/bree streets for nazgul in the event you don&#39;t go second. Council Courtyard lets you play a little for free (and face it what else is there?). Mithril Mine is my preference over Moria Stairway as damage +1 can backfire massively on your fellowship turn. The only other that there is a choice for is Anduin Wilderland as oppose to Confluence. That is simply a meta choice for your area (and thrarin/bounder is mighty helpful if you end up in the last few sites).<br>
<br>
A few last notes... Thankyou for reading through all that and for any constructive criticism. I&#39;m happy with my deck size so please suggest something to take out as well as something to put in. This is my first posting to decktech so be gentle. Also feel free to d-mail me if you have any questions about playing Ghost (or even e-mail me at reality_static@hotmail.com I check it more often). <br>
Finally most decks are designed to play with 80-100 twilight for shadow (see Michael Earleys The Twilight Pool and your Shadow deck)... this gives them about 30, have fun ;).<br>
